# PyTorch Transformer Interpretability: Belief-State Geometry in Non-Ergodic Sequence Models

**AI safety / mechanistic interpretability project analyzing how a PyTorch transformer represents hidden latent structure during next-token prediction.**

> **TL;DR** — I trained a small decoder-only transformer, implemented from scratch in PyTorch, on non-ergodic synthetic sequence data generated from a mixture of hidden Markov processes. I then analyzed the residual stream to test whether the model internally represents latent belief states and process identity. The main result is that the ground-truth belief state is almost perfectly linearly decodable from transformer activations (R² > 0.989), while process identity is only partially decodable (~60% accuracy vs. 33% chance). This suggests the model learns a compact, shared, low-dimensional internal geometry that prioritizes local predictive belief state over clean global source separation.

This project is based on and extends the ideas in [**"Transformers Learn Factored Representations"**](https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.02385) (Shai et al.), which shows that transformers trained via next-token prediction can factor their world into parts represented in orthogonal subspaces of the residual stream. Here I test what happens to that picture in a **non-ergodic** setting, where the "part" the model needs to factor out — which hidden process is active — is itself latent and never labeled.

---

## Why this project matters

Large language models are trained with next-token prediction, but the data they see is not generated by one stationary source. Real text comes from many hidden regimes: topics, speakers, tasks, domains, styles, instructions, and user intents. A capable model has to infer which latent regime it is in while also tracking the evolving state inside that regime.

This project builds a small, controlled version of that problem.

Each training sequence is generated entirely by one hidden stochastic process, but the transformer is never told which process generated it. To predict the next token well, the model has to infer both:

1. **Local belief state** — where it is within the active hidden process.
2. **Global process identity** — which hidden process is generating the current sequence.

This is relevant to **AI safety**, **mechanistic interpretability**, and **ML representation learning** because it provides a setting where the true latent variables are known exactly. That makes it possible to ask whether a transformer trained only through next-token prediction learns an interpretable internal representation.

---

## Research motivation

The central question is:

> When a transformer is trained only to predict the next token, does its residual stream recover the hidden belief-state geometry of the data-generating process?

This connects to several broader AI/ML questions:

- Do transformers learn Bayesian-style belief states internally?
- Are latent variables linearly represented in the residual stream?
- How does context length change the geometry of internal representations?
- Does a model cleanly separate task/process identity from local predictive state?
- Can small controlled models help us understand representation formation in larger LLMs?
- What kinds of hidden structure does next-token prediction induce?

These questions are directly relevant to interpretability and AI safety because larger models may also represent hidden variables such as task, intent, topic, speaker, world state, or instruction regime inside their activations.

---

## Background

The data comes from three hidden stochastic sequence-generating processes (Mess3 processes), each with three hidden states and three emitted symbols. Given an observed token history, the exact Bayesian belief state over hidden states can be computed in closed form.

| Process | α    | x    | Character                                                  |
|---------|------|------|-------------------------------------------------------------|
| P1      | 0.95 | 0.02 | Very strong structure, belief concentrated near simplex vertices |
| P2      | 0.90 | 0.05 | Strong structure, intermediate spread                       |
| P3      | 0.85 | 0.12 | Moderate structure, broadest, multi-scale belief geometry    |

A single process has a well-defined belief-state geometry, living on a 2-dimensional probability simplex. But when the dataset is a mixture of several processes — and each individual sequence comes entirely from one process — the overall dataset becomes **non-ergodic**. The model must infer both the active process and the belief state within that process, with no explicit label for either.

This creates a clean toy model for studying how transformers represent hidden context.

---

## What I implemented

I implemented the full experiment end-to-end:

- Synthetic non-ergodic sequence generation
- Multiple hidden Markov generative processes
- Small decoder-only transformer implemented from scratch in PyTorch
- Causal self-attention with an explicit triangular mask
- Next-token prediction training loop
- Residual-stream activation extraction
- Exact Bayesian belief-state computation
- PCA and effective-dimensionality analysis
- Linear probing of belief state from activations
- Linear decoding of process identity
- Geometry visualization across layers and context positions
- Research writeup with pre-registered predictions and interpretation

The goal was not just to train a model, but to understand what the model learned internally.

---

## Model

The transformer was intentionally small so that its representations could be analyzed directly.

**Architecture**

- Decoder-only causal transformer
- Token and positional embeddings
- Multi-head causal self-attention
- MLP blocks
- Residual connections
- Layer normalization
- Explicit residual-stream collection

**Training setup**

- 2 transformer blocks
- 64-dimensional residual stream
- 2 attention heads
- MLP hidden size 256
- Context length 16
- Batch size 256
- Adam optimizer
- Learning rate 5e-4
- Approximately 101K parameters
- Next-token cross-entropy objective

The model was implemented directly in PyTorch rather than using a high-level transformer library, so the code exposes the architecture, training loop, attention mechanism, activation collection, and analysis pipeline clearly.

---

## Pre-registered prediction

Before analyzing the trained model, I made a prediction about what geometry the residual stream should learn, and derived it mathematically as far as I could.

Each individual process has a 3-state belief vector, which lives in a 2-dimensional probability simplex (3 states, normalized to sum to 1, → 2 degrees of freedom). In the mixed non-ergodic setting, the full joint belief over (process, hidden state) is a 9-dimensional joint distribution, likewise normalized — formally an 8-simplex. Treating process identity and within-process state as two pseudo-factors gives:

- a **lower bound of (3−1) + (3−1) = 4 dimensions**, if the network shares a single compact belief subspace across all three processes, or
- an **upper bound of 3 × 2 = 6 dimensions**, if it instead allocates a fully separate, orthogonal 2D subspace per process.

I predicted the true effective dimensionality would land closer to the 4D lower bound, given the structural similarity between the three processes and the general pressure toward dimensionally efficient representations.

I considered three possible geometries:

### 1. Fully factored geometry

The model could represent process identity and within-process belief state in cleanly separated subspaces. This would make both belief state and process identity highly linearly decodable.

### 2. Fully joint geometry

The model could represent the full joint distribution over process identity and hidden state, without cleanly separating the factors. This would be faithful but higher-dimensional (~6–8D).

### 3. Partially shared geometry

The model could reuse a shared low-dimensional belief-state geometry across processes, while representing process identity only partially. This would lead to very strong belief-state decoding but weaker process-identity decoding, close to the 4D lower bound.

My prediction was closest to option 3: a compact, partially shared representation where belief state is easier to decode than process identity.

---

## Results

### 1. The PyTorch transformer learned the sequence structure

The model converged to a cross-entropy loss of approximately 0.74, substantially below the uniform-token baseline of log(3) ≈ 1.099.

This confirms that the model learned meaningful sequential structure rather than only matching token frequencies.

### 2. The residual stream became low-dimensional

The raw embedding layer required about 12 principal components to explain 95% of activation variance. After the first transformer layer, this compressed to roughly 3 dimensions. After the second layer, the representation stabilized around 4 dimensions — matching the predicted lower bound.

This suggests the transformer reorganized high-dimensional token and position embeddings into a compact latent representation useful for prediction.

### 3. Belief state was almost perfectly linearly decodable

Using the known generative process, I computed the exact ground-truth Bayesian belief state at each context position, then trained linear probes from residual-stream activations to the true belief state.

The belief state was almost perfectly recoverable from the residual stream, with R² > 0.989 across context positions.

This is the main result: the transformer learned an internal representation that closely tracks the true latent belief state, even though it was trained only with next-token prediction.

### 4. Process identity was only partially decodable

A linear classifier trained on residual-stream activations decoded the generating process above chance, reaching roughly 60% accuracy by late context positions.

This is well above the 33% chance baseline, but far below perfect classification. The result suggests the model does not cleanly separate the three processes. Instead, it learns a shared representation where process identity is partially entangled with local belief-state geometry.

### 5. Geometry changed with context

At early context positions, activations were mostly organized by the most recent token. At later context positions, the residual stream developed a richer low-dimensional geometry.

When colored by ground-truth belief coordinates, the representation showed smooth gradients: nearby points in activation space corresponded to nearby belief states. This indicates the model learned a continuous internal geometry related to the Bayesian belief state of the sequence.

---

## Interpretation

The key result is an asymmetry:

- **Belief state is almost perfectly linearly represented.**
- **Process identity is only partially linearly represented.**

This suggests the transformer prioritizes the local predictive state needed for next-token prediction over clean global source identification.

In larger language models, an analogous effect could appear when a model tracks local context well but does not fully commit to a single task, domain, user intent, or instruction regime. This may help explain why model behavior can be prompt-sensitive even when local predictions look coherent.

This project therefore provides a small AI safety-relevant testbed for studying how next-token prediction produces hidden internal structure.

### Connection to computational neuroscience

This setup is also a clean analogue of a problem I've worked on directly: using GLM-HMMs to identify latent behavioral states in animals from sequences of observations, where an animal's underlying strategy switches between discrete regimes (e.g. engaged vs. biased) that must be inferred from behavior alone rather than being directly observed. The non-ergodic Mess3 setting is a minimal, mathematically tractable version of the same nested-inference problem — a fast, local belief update within a regime, nested inside a slower identification of which regime is active. That connection is part of what motivated applying the same kind of latent-state analysis to a transformer's own internal activations (see *Possible extensions* below).

---

## AI safety and interpretability relevance

This project is useful as a toy model for AI safety because the ground-truth latent variables are known exactly. That makes it possible to evaluate whether representation-analysis tools recover the true internal structure.

It demonstrates:

- How next-token prediction can induce belief-like internal variables
- How residual-stream activations can encode latent state
- How linear probes can recover hidden variables
- How process identity can remain entangled even when prediction works well
- How controlled synthetic tasks can help test mechanistic interpretability hypotheses
- How small PyTorch models can be used to study questions relevant to larger LLMs

