---

## Possible extensions

With more time, I would extend this project in several directions:

- Run multiple random seeds and report confidence intervals
- Add held-out train/test splits for all linear probes
- Scale the number of hidden processes
- Vary process similarity and measure when identity decoding improves
- Increase transformer depth and context length
- Introduce mid-sequence process switches
- Analyze attention heads for process-inference behavior
- Compare residual-stream probes with attention-pattern analysis
- Measure subspace overlap between per-process representations
- Test whether sparse autoencoders recover belief-state features
- Apply latent-state models (e.g. GLM-HMMs) to the model's own activation trajectories, to test whether it resolves process identity through discrete jumps or smooth interpolation

---

## References

- Shai et al., ["Transformers Learn Factored Representations"](https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.02385) — the primary paper this project is based on and extends into the non-ergodic setting.
- Shai et al., ["Transformers Represent Belief State Geometry in their Residual Stream"](https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.15943) — earlier work establishing that belief-state geometry is linearly represented in transformer activations, which motivates the belief-state decoding analysis here.

---

## Summary

This project shows that a small PyTorch transformer trained on a controlled non-ergodic next-token prediction task learns a compact internal representation of latent belief state.

I built the full pipeline myself — data generation, model implementation, training, activation extraction, exact belief-state computation, probing, visualization, and interpretation. The main result is that the true Bayesian belief state is almost perfectly linearly decodable from the residual stream, while process identity is only partially decodable. This makes the project a compact but complete example of studying transformer representations, latent-state inference, mechanistic interpretability, and AI safety-relevant questions about hidden structure in model activations.
